Be concise in your response.
Always use meaningful variable, method, function, and class names — don't name x, y, z, a, etc.

🚧 Cursor Rule: API Feature Implementation

When implementing any feature that interacts with the backend (Dio/REST/etc), you MUST follow this structure:

1. Data Layer (Implementation only)

Create/update repository implementation inside:

lib/src/data/repository/
Responsibilities:
Call Dio via shared client from lib/src/core/network/
Map DTO ↔ Domain Entities
Catch DioException and map to OperationFailure
❌ Do NOT expose data models to presentation layer
2. Domain Layer (Pure business logic)
a. Repository Contract

Define abstract repository in:

lib/src/domain/repository/
Return TaskEither<OperationFailure, T> (fpdart)
b. Use Case (MANDATORY)

Create a dedicated use case in:

lib/src/domain/use_case/
Each use case = one clear action
No UI / Flutter imports allowed
3. Presentation Layer
a. Bloc (MANDATORY)

Location:

lib/src/presentation/<feature>/bloc/
Must include:
event
state
bloc
Uses only use cases, never repositories directly
b. Screen

Location:

lib/src/presentation/<feature>/<feature>_screen.dart
Responsibilities:
Provide Bloc
Handle navigation
Compose UI
c. Widgets (MANDATORY separation)

All UI components go inside:

lib/src/presentation/<feature>/widgets/
❌ No large UI inside screen
❌ No business logic inside widgets
4. Dependency Injection
Register:
Repository implementation
Use case
Bloc

Inside:

lib/src/di/register_module.dart
🔥 Strict Rules (Non-negotiable)
❌ UI must NEVER call Dio directly
❌ Bloc must NEVER call repository implementation directly
❌ Skip layers = NOT allowed (no shortcuts)
❌ No logic inside widgets except UI logic
❌ No mixing data models with domain entities
✅ Flow Summary
UI (Screen)
   ↓
Bloc
   ↓
Use Case
   ↓
Repository (abstract)
   ↓
Repository Impl (Dio)
   ↓
API
🧠 Naming Convention

Example: CreateGroup

Use case → create_group_use_case.dart
Bloc → create_group_bloc.dart
Screen → create_group_screen.dart
Widgets → widgets/
Repo method → createGroup()
💡 Optional (but highly recommended)
Use freezed for:
states
events
models
Use OperationFailure for non-auth errors
Always return TaskEither<OperationFailure, Result>
